        "### ❓ Question 5.1.1: Justify Your Chunking Choice\n",
        "\n",
        "**Write your answer here:** [Why did you choose these chunk size and overlap values? What trade-offs did you consider?]"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "lshpeSMquVBh"
      },
      "source": [
        "**YOUR ANSWER:**\n",
        "\n",
        "I chose a chuck size of 120 words and an overlap of 30 words. I believe a chunk size of 120 strikes a good balance in the amount of context fed into the LLM. AARs are written in a concise manner, usually getting straight to the point. So you don’t need to retrieve too much information to get to the meat of the material. That being said, an overlap of 30 words should give the chunk enough “padding” between each other to provide enough context on the topic at hand. A chunk size that is too small (eg 50) could result in not getting to the meat of the material at all and a chunk size too large (eg 500) would add extra noise to the LLM and would end up retrieving the entire AAR. As for overlap, an overlap that is too small (eg 0) would not provide enough context between retrieved chunks and an overlap too large (eg 100) would just be redundant because our chunk size is already 120 words. An overlap of 100 would basically take over the whole chunk and is a waste of memory.\n",
        "\n",
