      },
      "source": [
        "### ❓ Question 11.2: Leadership & Ethics\n",
        "\n",
        "**Write your answer here:** [Discuss when you should trust vs. verify vs. not use AI outputs]"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "582WzwnuuVBs"
      },
      "source": [
        "**YOUR ANSWER:**\n",
        "\n",
        "Leaders should only trust this system after checking its citations. If the claim the system makes is consistent with the fact (cited source), then you can trust it. However, if the cited source deviates from the generated claim, then you should reject its conclusions. Over-relying on AAR synthesis can cause people to blindly trust the system's output without double checking its sources. It’s analogous to news on social media apps. If you just take the first thing you see as gospel, without checking other sources, then you will make ill decisions based on incorrect information. You can design safeguards by integrating an ROE, forcing the system to always cite its sources and state when it cannot find the answer in the provided sources. Additionally, you can create a system that will check if the cited sources match up with the output of the LLM."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "DgdD2b5BuVBs"
      },
      "source": [
        "### ❓ Question 11.3: Precision vs. Recall\n",
        "\n",
        "**Write your answer here:** [Explain the trade-off between retrieving more chunks vs. fewer chunks]"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "qqnQoIfNuVBs"
      },
      "source": [
        "**YOUR ANSWER:**\n",
        "\n",
        "Retrieving more chunks (high recall) is great for a synthesizing task where you want a summary of a wide breadth of information whereas ensuring all chunks are highly relevant (high precision) is great for a specific Q&A task where you want an answer about a specific topic at hand. For a military leader, if you want to find patterns within the system (eg recurring flaws) you want to prioritize recall and retrieve a lot of chunks. On the other hand, if you want to know why that specific flaw is causing a bottleneck in the operation, you want to prioritize precision and ensure all chunks are highly relevant (resulting in fewer retrieved chunks). There are tradeoffs of course. If there are too few chunks, there might not be enough context provided to the LLM to provide an answer that covers all concepts required to provide a cohesive claim. On the other hand, if there are too many chunks, you run the risk of adding extra information/noise to the system which can cause the LLM to hallucinate if it gets overwhelmed by the large context window."
      ]
    },
